WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.840
I'm excited to talk about making PowerPoint presentations with R Markdown today.

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:16.959
This is a project that we've been working on for a while now, and it's nice to finally

00:00:16.959 --> 00:00:22.440
present some of the material.

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:27.020
So you're probably wondering, why would you want to create a PowerPoint presentation from

00:00:27.020 --> 00:00:28.020
R Markdown?

00:00:28.020 --> 00:00:34.900
Well, there's a number of reasons, but I'm going to point out a few.

00:00:34.900 --> 00:00:37.779
So one reason is that everyone knows PowerPoint.

00:00:37.779 --> 00:00:41.360
It's a standard communication tool, especially used in business.

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:44.259
People learn to speak the language of PowerPoint.

00:00:44.259 --> 00:00:47.020
And the fact of the matter is, it's very useful, because it works.

00:00:47.020 --> 00:00:48.259
It's very flexible.

00:00:48.259 --> 00:00:50.139
You can make slides fast.

00:00:50.139 --> 00:00:52.680
And everyone has personal experience with it.

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:53.820
Some people love it.

00:00:53.820 --> 00:00:55.660
Some people, not so much.

00:00:55.660 --> 00:01:01.139
But everyone has an opinion on it, because we've all touched this tool.

00:01:01.139 --> 00:01:07.980
But your work, of course, is coded in R. And that's because your code is your product.

00:01:07.980 --> 00:01:10.820
So your output is a manifestation of your code.

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:15.220
So plots, tables, model output, that's all coming from your code.

00:01:15.220 --> 00:01:18.540
Well, that's where R Markdown becomes very useful.

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:20.660
R Markdown makes your work reproducible.

00:01:20.660 --> 00:01:24.779
You can weave text and code to produce elegantly formatted output.

00:01:24.779 --> 00:01:29.260
You can use things like R Notebooks for doing interactive analyses.

00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:34.660
R Markdown, if you haven't used it, will allow you to create a number of different

00:01:34.660 --> 00:01:41.480
output types, reports, apps, dashboards, HTML docs, PDFs, Word documents, but not PowerPoint.

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:43.980
Not until now.

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:47.320
So now you can make PowerPoint presentations with R Markdown.

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:53.199
As of RStudio version 1.2, you can render PowerPoint presentations from the IDE.

00:01:53.199 --> 00:01:56.400
This combines two great things, PowerPoint and R Markdown.

00:01:56.400 --> 00:02:00.519
You can think of it as the Reese's Peanut Butter Cup of presentation software.

00:02:00.519 --> 00:02:04.160
I'm not sure which one's the chocolate and which one's the peanut butter, but you can

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:09.220
tell I put this together during the Halloween time period.

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:20.559
So let me show you a quick demo of doing PowerPoint presentations with RStudio.

00:02:20.559 --> 00:02:24.380
So this is the RStudio preview version 1.2.

00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:37.660
If I go up to File, New File, R Markdown, and then I choose Presentation down at the

00:02:37.660 --> 00:02:42.059
bottom, I have an option to do PowerPoint.

00:02:42.059 --> 00:02:43.740
Click OK.

00:02:43.740 --> 00:02:45.059
And this is an R Markdown document.

00:02:45.059 --> 00:02:51.539
Again, if you've never seen R Markdown, it will contain the prose, some narrative, plus

00:02:51.539 --> 00:02:56.179
some R code chunks, some things about R that you might want to include in your document.

00:02:56.179 --> 00:03:00.820
And then the output type here is PowerPoint presentation.

00:03:00.820 --> 00:03:04.460
And the way you create the PowerPoint presentation is you hit this knit button.

00:03:05.460 --> 00:03:08.100
So when I hit this, I'll give it a name.

00:03:12.860 --> 00:03:22.059
And it generates a PowerPoint deck with the content, some bullets, some R code output,

00:03:22.059 --> 00:03:25.220
and a nice little plot.

00:03:25.220 --> 00:03:28.839
Now, if you don't want to use the RStudio IDE, that's fine.

00:03:28.839 --> 00:03:30.940
You don't have to use the RStudio IDE.

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:33.740
You can always render this programmatically.

00:03:33.740 --> 00:03:35.779
This all works with open-source software.

00:03:35.779 --> 00:03:38.779
You can do this inside of an R console.

00:03:38.779 --> 00:03:44.740
Type in render, give it the name and the output format, and that will also generate the PowerPoint output.

00:03:54.339 --> 00:03:55.339
All right.

00:03:55.339 --> 00:03:58.259
So some of the benefits of using R Markdown here.

00:03:58.259 --> 00:04:02.779
Well, in this book, R for Data Science, there's this lovely chapter at the end of this book.

00:04:02.779 --> 00:04:05.619
If you haven't seen it, I recommend that you read it.

00:04:05.619 --> 00:04:11.539
It's about R Markdown, about communicating insights to decision makers.

00:04:11.539 --> 00:04:17.940
And it makes the point that R Markdown is a great way to influence other people in your organization

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:23.579
and other people that will be making decisions based on the work that you do in your data science.

00:04:23.579 --> 00:04:28.179
We'll allow you to do better data science because you'll be collaborating with other data scientists

00:04:28.179 --> 00:04:32.420
who are able to read your code, understand your code, and reproduce your code.

00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:35.899
And it gives you this nice environment in which you can do data science.

00:04:35.899 --> 00:04:42.019
When you put your narrative together with the code and the output into a single document,

00:04:42.019 --> 00:04:45.899
I would argue through personal experience that you do better data science.

00:04:45.899 --> 00:04:50.859
It allows you to think more clearly and understand why you're doing what you're doing.

00:04:50.859 --> 00:04:56.019
From a presentation standpoint with PowerPoint, I think one of the big takeaways here is that

00:04:56.019 --> 00:04:59.500
you're just going to spend a lot less time iterating on presentation slides

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:02.579
and a lot more time doing what you do best, which is data science.

00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:07.019
All right, so how does it work?

00:05:10.179 --> 00:05:18.100
Well, you write your code in R Markdown format, and then you knit the code with the Knitter package.

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:25.859
And what Knitter does is it takes your R Markdown code and it converts it into Markdown format.

00:05:25.859 --> 00:05:32.179
And Markdown format is a universal format that can be put into this other system called Pandoc.

00:05:32.179 --> 00:05:37.299
And Pandoc is what actually converts the Markdown document into PowerPoint.

00:05:37.299 --> 00:05:41.339
Now, all of this is already bundled into the IDE, so it's seamless,

00:05:41.339 --> 00:05:43.739
but this is what's happening under the covers.

00:05:43.739 --> 00:05:46.940
So I want to focus on this Pandoc piece for a second.

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:49.980
Well, what is Pandoc?

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:53.940
Well, Pandoc is the open source software that converts files from one format into another.

00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:56.179
You can think of it as a Swiss Army knife.

00:05:56.179 --> 00:06:01.019
And PowerPoint output was added to Pandoc in Pandoc version 2.

00:06:01.019 --> 00:06:06.299
The initial release was in December 2017, and then there was a number of progressive updates

00:06:06.299 --> 00:06:12.579
that happened at the beginning of this year to allow you to create this PowerPoint output.

00:06:12.579 --> 00:06:17.380
And Pandoc is bundled into the RStudio IDE.

00:06:17.380 --> 00:06:23.019
And the RStudio IDE version 1.2 has the ability to create PowerPoint documents

00:06:23.019 --> 00:06:27.779
and RStudio Connect as a version 1.6.4, which came out a few months ago,

00:06:27.779 --> 00:06:32.940
that also has the ability to support PowerPoint documents.

00:06:32.940 --> 00:06:40.019
Now, a lot of this work here with Pandoc was done by a developer, a Haskell developer.

00:06:40.019 --> 00:06:41.500
Pandoc's written Haskell.

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:49.940
And he works out of, he's a professor at Johns Hopkins University, and his name's Jesse Rosenthal.

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:55.059
And Jesse's actually on the call today, so it's great to have him here and joining the webinar.

00:06:55.059 --> 00:07:00.459
But most of this development work was, that allows us to convert documents

00:07:00.459 --> 00:07:02.380
into PowerPoint, was done by Jesse.

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:13.579
R Markdown's not the only way to do document conversion into PowerPoint.

00:07:13.579 --> 00:07:16.700
You have these other R packages that you might have used.

00:07:16.700 --> 00:07:18.100
And these are great R packages.

00:07:18.100 --> 00:07:19.700
I've used some of them.

00:07:19.700 --> 00:07:24.420
They allow you to have fine-grained control over what happens on those slides.

00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:32.420
And some of these will have features that aren't available in the Markdown format, conversion format.

00:07:32.420 --> 00:07:34.899
So, these packages are still relevant.

00:07:34.899 --> 00:07:37.299
You might still find these very useful.

00:07:39.420 --> 00:07:46.859
Let's talk about use cases for creating PowerPoint presentations from R Markdown.

00:07:47.179 --> 00:07:53.660
The first one is to render the presentation, and then customize the presentation.

00:07:53.660 --> 00:07:59.420
And that's probably going to be a very common use case for your PowerPoint slides.

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:02.339
You're going to output the text, the tables, and the plots to PowerPoint.

00:08:02.339 --> 00:08:06.500
And then you're going to modify these or copy these into your final presentation.

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:08.739
I'll give you an example.

00:08:09.739 --> 00:08:17.140
This is a notebook that analyzes bank data.

00:08:17.140 --> 00:08:23.700
And in the course of this analysis, I create a whole bunch of visualizations that are interesting.

00:08:23.700 --> 00:08:28.500
And normally, what I would do with these visualizations is I would take these,

00:08:28.500 --> 00:08:34.460
and I'd copy these one at a time into my PowerPoint presentation.

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:38.700
My PowerPoint presentation would become a mess, and then I'd lose track of which ones are which,

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:44.940
and I'd have to go back, and when I go back to update my analysis, then things become out of sync.

00:08:44.940 --> 00:08:50.940
It'd be much better just to be able to render all of the slides in one shot from this notebook.

00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:54.700
And that's what you can do with the PowerPoint output.

00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:59.539
So, I come up here and say, knit this presentation.

00:08:59.539 --> 00:09:06.419
This will go through and spin up a new R session, run all of the R code through that session,

00:09:06.419 --> 00:09:12.900
and then generate a PowerPoint presentation.

00:09:12.900 --> 00:09:15.419
Okay, so here's the slides.

00:09:15.419 --> 00:09:19.260
You can see that I've got my narrative again.

00:09:19.260 --> 00:09:22.500
And then I've got some graphs here.

00:09:22.500 --> 00:09:25.700
And I can take these graphs, and I can copy these into my final presentation.

00:09:25.700 --> 00:09:28.739
I've got a table, and that's really great, too, right?

00:09:28.739 --> 00:09:34.859
And I can, if I don't like the order here, I can just move these around if I need to.

00:09:34.859 --> 00:09:41.099
If I want to change the background, change my template, I can do that as well.

00:09:41.099 --> 00:09:45.059
Choose a different template.

00:09:45.059 --> 00:09:50.859
If I'm not happy with the table, the table renders as a PowerPoint table,

00:09:50.859 --> 00:09:55.619
so I can go ahead and change that table design.

00:09:55.619 --> 00:10:01.940
And I can come in here and say, you know, I've got more than one data source.

00:10:01.940 --> 00:10:02.940
I've got data sources.

00:10:03.020 --> 00:10:05.859
I'm going to change that.

00:10:05.859 --> 00:10:08.979
And now I've really broken the reproducibility paradigm, right?

00:10:08.979 --> 00:10:11.340
I've actually gone through and made some changes.

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:15.659
And now if I go back and redo the slides, I'm going to have to do those again.

00:10:15.659 --> 00:10:20.539
But I'd argue that you're much better off because you can produce a lot of these

00:10:20.539 --> 00:10:25.099
at the same time, and you can keep them anchored to that R Markdown document

00:10:25.099 --> 00:10:27.460
that explains what you're doing.

00:10:27.460 --> 00:10:30.539
So we think this will be a pretty common use case for taking slides

00:10:30.539 --> 00:10:32.299
and then manipulating them.

00:10:32.299 --> 00:10:35.380
People like to customize their PowerPoint presentations.

00:10:35.380 --> 00:10:40.419
And chances are, your slides are going to be one part of a larger presentation

00:10:40.419 --> 00:10:45.059
that ends up getting delivered to the executive or the client

00:10:45.059 --> 00:10:47.299
or whoever you're trying to communicate with.

00:10:47.299 --> 00:10:48.820
And that will work great in this workflow.

00:10:48.820 --> 00:11:03.700
The other use case is to publish to RStudio Connect.

00:11:03.700 --> 00:11:04.700
What is RStudio Connect?

00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:08.820
It's a publishing platform for R. It runs your R code, and it allows you

00:11:08.820 --> 00:11:13.340
to share your Shiny apps, R Markdown reports, and much, much more.

00:11:13.340 --> 00:11:15.219
So in this use case, what you're going to do is you're going

00:11:15.219 --> 00:11:19.820
to output the entire presentation with R Markdown, and then you're going

00:11:19.820 --> 00:11:23.059
to render updates programmatically on a schedule.

00:11:23.059 --> 00:11:26.659
And then you'll distribute those PowerPoint presentations by email,

00:11:26.659 --> 00:11:29.299
and you can even design them to accept user inputs.

00:11:29.299 --> 00:11:33.260
So this is a little bit easier to show than to explain.

00:11:36.260 --> 00:11:38.340
Here's another presentation that I'm using.

00:11:38.340 --> 00:11:40.979
It's the stock data.

00:11:40.979 --> 00:11:43.419
And this is a parameterized R Markdown document.

00:11:43.419 --> 00:11:47.500
And if you haven't seen parameterized R Markdown before, they're extremely powerful.

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:50.539
You set up parameters here and then inputs here.

00:11:50.539 --> 00:11:54.940
This is going to be the Tesla stock ticker symbol.

00:11:54.940 --> 00:12:00.940
And if I want to call that in my R Markdown document, I just use param string symbol.

00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:06.419
So these become very useful in their own right, even regardless of how you're, you know,

00:12:06.419 --> 00:12:09.619
accepting user inputs or what output formats you're using.

00:12:09.619 --> 00:12:15.619
Parameterized R Markdown, parameterization is extremely powerful in R Markdown documents.

00:12:15.619 --> 00:12:18.460
But here what I can do is I can say I'm going to knit this thing.

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:20.580
I'll go ahead and knit it with parameters.

00:12:20.580 --> 00:12:24.099
And I'll choose like the IBM report, I guess, right?

00:12:24.099 --> 00:12:26.140
I'll knit this document.

00:12:32.820 --> 00:12:38.179
Great. Now I have a document for the IBM candlestick chart.

00:12:38.179 --> 00:12:39.380
And this is what I want.

00:12:39.380 --> 00:12:46.419
But I can't anticipate everybody's needs here with all of the different stock tickers

00:12:46.419 --> 00:12:51.299
that they might need, nor am I able to automate this every day.

00:12:51.299 --> 00:12:54.260
You know, I don't have the ability to update this every day.

00:12:54.260 --> 00:12:57.340
I have to be able to automate it with the system.

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:00.260
So I want to make sure that this report gets generated daily and sent

00:13:00.260 --> 00:13:03.219
out to the people that are interested in it.

00:13:03.219 --> 00:13:06.260
So what I do is I publish this to RStudio Connect.

00:13:06.299 --> 00:13:09.659
And I can do that with this publish button and choose RStudio Connect.

00:13:09.659 --> 00:13:13.260
And this is what RStudio Connect looks like.

00:13:18.020 --> 00:13:19.580
Here's the default report.

00:13:19.580 --> 00:13:21.219
That's going to be the Tesla report.

00:13:21.219 --> 00:13:29.179
If I want to change the report ticker, I can go in here and I can say I want to change IBM, right?

00:13:29.179 --> 00:13:30.340
And you run that report.

00:13:30.340 --> 00:13:33.539
I'm not going to run the report because I've already done it for you.

00:13:33.539 --> 00:13:34.780
It's right here.

00:13:34.780 --> 00:13:39.020
And then if I want to, I can go ahead and email this report to myself, right?

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:43.419
Or I can come in here and I can schedule this report to run every day

00:13:43.419 --> 00:13:47.500
and then send me an email when it's complete.

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:50.580
And I can add more people to this report.

00:13:50.580 --> 00:13:57.580
And what that report looks like is if I go to my inbox, you can see that I just got the report.

00:13:57.580 --> 00:14:02.659
It's got this nice graphic here that tells me that IBM closed at 1.20.03.

00:14:02.659 --> 00:14:11.140
And I come down here to the end and I can see that I've attached the PowerPoint presentation to the email.

00:14:11.140 --> 00:14:16.460
And again, this is going to be the updated report that I just ran.

00:14:16.460 --> 00:14:22.979
So you can see that this would be a very useful way to communicate your insights with a lot of people

00:14:22.979 --> 00:14:28.140
who prefer to get their information by email and PowerPoint.

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:31.580
I personally know a lot of people in that boat that would like to get their information

00:14:31.580 --> 00:14:34.780
communicated to them in email and PowerPoint.

00:14:34.780 --> 00:14:36.739
Perhaps you do as well.

00:14:36.739 --> 00:14:40.700
The nice thing here is that you only have to write the code once

00:14:40.700 --> 00:14:46.979
and then RStudio Connect can handle the scheduling and the distribution

00:14:46.979 --> 00:14:49.979
and accept the user inputs systematically.

00:14:57.500 --> 00:14:58.940
So those are some use cases.

00:14:58.940 --> 00:15:00.419
Let's talk about features.

00:15:02.580 --> 00:15:08.979
So the PowerPoint output accepts most of the markdown features

00:15:08.979 --> 00:15:12.140
that are supported in other document formats.

00:15:12.140 --> 00:15:16.900
For example, inline formatting is supported.

00:15:16.900 --> 00:15:21.299
So this is what the inline formatting looks like in your code.

00:15:21.299 --> 00:15:25.299
And this is how it gets rendered in the PowerPoint.

00:15:25.299 --> 00:15:30.739
Supports lists, LaTeX.

00:15:30.780 --> 00:15:41.900
So if you're putting in math equations, hyperlinks, of course, block quotes, images from the web.

00:15:41.900 --> 00:15:47.900
This went out and snagged an image from the web and then put it into my slide.

00:15:47.900 --> 00:15:48.780
Images from file.

00:15:48.780 --> 00:15:53.260
This actually took an image from a file and put it into my slide.

00:15:53.260 --> 00:15:56.700
You can add captions to images.

00:15:56.700 --> 00:15:59.820
You can add a linked caption to the image.

00:15:59.820 --> 00:16:01.260
Or you can link the image.

00:16:01.260 --> 00:16:08.539
In this case, what happens is if I click this image, this will take me to the R for Data Science page.

00:16:08.539 --> 00:16:09.780
Supports tables.

00:16:09.780 --> 00:16:15.940
So you write your tables and markdown code that looks like this and they get rendered like this.

00:16:15.940 --> 00:16:20.219
Notice there's a caption down here.

00:16:20.219 --> 00:16:24.460
Also supports these really nifty features like columns.

00:16:24.460 --> 00:16:25.619
So columns are great.

00:16:25.619 --> 00:16:29.859
What you do here is you create this fence.

00:16:29.859 --> 00:16:32.140
This is called a fence div.

00:16:32.140 --> 00:16:35.380
And you put all the contents for the first column here.

00:16:35.380 --> 00:16:38.859
And you put all the contents for the second column here.

00:16:38.859 --> 00:16:41.780
And then it will show up in your two-column layout.

00:16:41.780 --> 00:16:44.539
It's called the two-content layout.

00:16:44.539 --> 00:16:49.460
Two columns and two contents and two columns.

00:16:49.460 --> 00:16:51.020
Supports speaker notes.

00:16:51.020 --> 00:16:53.340
Speaker notes are very useful.

00:16:53.340 --> 00:16:59.979
Again, you put a fence div here and you can put the speaker notes that will render in the presentation.

00:16:59.979 --> 00:17:01.419
And templates.

00:17:01.419 --> 00:17:03.260
The templates become very useful also.

00:17:03.260 --> 00:17:10.900
And I will be talking about that a little bit later.

00:17:10.900 --> 00:17:14.060
And of course, this translation supports R code.

00:17:14.060 --> 00:17:15.420
That's the whole point of this, right?

00:17:15.420 --> 00:17:19.140
You want to be able to put R code into your R markdown documents.

00:17:19.140 --> 00:17:21.339
What kind of R code does it support?

00:17:21.339 --> 00:17:24.339
Well, any of the R code that's in your R code chunks.

00:17:24.339 --> 00:17:27.219
And that typically is going to look like code.

00:17:27.219 --> 00:17:30.900
And your code gets highlighted.

00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:36.900
The syntax of your code gets highlighted in the output automatically.

00:17:36.900 --> 00:17:37.579
Tables.

00:17:37.579 --> 00:17:45.420
So if you call the cable function, which is in Knitter, it will create a table in PowerPoint.

00:17:45.420 --> 00:17:53.939
ggplot or any other visualization that will render that image on a content slide.

00:17:53.939 --> 00:18:03.540
And if you do something interactive, like in HTML widgets, here I'm using diagraphs, the rendering process will go,

00:18:03.540 --> 00:18:09.099
if you have installed the webshot package, the rendering process will go and grab a web screenshot

00:18:09.099 --> 00:18:15.219
of your interactive visualization and include it in your PowerPoint presentation.

00:18:19.699 --> 00:18:21.060
And finally, Shiny.

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:26.140
How do you include Shiny in your PowerPoint presentations?

00:18:26.140 --> 00:18:28.060
Shiny is interactive.

00:18:28.060 --> 00:18:29.819
PowerPoint presentations are static.

00:18:29.819 --> 00:18:32.500
So obviously, you can't put Shiny inside of PowerPoint.

00:18:32.500 --> 00:18:34.219
That would be ridiculous.

00:18:34.219 --> 00:18:40.900
What you're going to do instead is you're going to put a static image of your Shiny application on your slide

00:18:40.900 --> 00:18:51.739
and then link that to your Shiny application, which will be hosted in Shiny Apps IO, RStudio Connect, or Shiny Server.

00:18:51.739 --> 00:18:56.979
So I will show you an example.

00:18:56.979 --> 00:19:01.180
In the course of my analysis, I created this Shiny application.

00:19:01.180 --> 00:19:03.459
It's a customer tracker app.

00:19:03.459 --> 00:19:09.699
The nice thing about this is it allows me to drill down into subgroups and other segments.

00:19:09.699 --> 00:19:16.300
But obviously, I can't put all of those segments or groups into a PowerPoint presentation.

00:19:16.300 --> 00:19:18.300
So what do I do?

00:19:21.979 --> 00:19:30.979
I go back to the code and I include this line, include app, and I put the URL for that application into my presentation.

00:19:31.979 --> 00:19:40.979
And when I knit this process, it's going to go and take a screenshot of that Shiny application and put it back into my presentation.

00:19:40.979 --> 00:19:50.699
For example, this deck shows the total segment and the total group, gives me some high-level results and some details.

00:19:50.699 --> 00:19:56.500
And then it says, use the Shiny app to explore other segments and groups.

00:19:57.219 --> 00:20:01.339
And this image here is a linked image.

00:20:01.339 --> 00:20:13.699
I can click on this image and it seemed to have lost my PowerPoint presentation.

00:20:13.699 --> 00:20:15.699
Let's try that again.

00:20:27.500 --> 00:20:29.500
All right.

00:20:29.500 --> 00:20:33.500
So when I click on this image, this will take me back to my Shiny application.

00:20:36.500 --> 00:20:47.500
And this Shiny, this will allow your viewers to interact with your application, choose a subgroup.

00:20:47.500 --> 00:21:00.500
And I've even put a download link here to take a snapshot of this report that is formatted in Excel and allows you to see the report that you've dug into.

00:21:00.500 --> 00:21:04.500
It gives you all the data to do cross tabs if you want to do that.

00:21:04.500 --> 00:21:19.500
But what I've done here is I've tied a PowerPoint presentation, an Excel output, and a Shiny application and put them all on top of the same, yeah, the same code base.

00:21:35.500 --> 00:21:36.500
All right.

00:21:36.500 --> 00:21:38.500
So let's talk about resources.

00:21:38.500 --> 00:21:40.500
What resources are available?

00:21:42.500 --> 00:21:46.500
The first place to go to get help would probably be rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

00:21:46.500 --> 00:21:49.500
That's our website about R Markdown.

00:21:49.500 --> 00:21:52.500
There's also a new book that's out called R Markdown, the Definitive Guide.

00:21:52.500 --> 00:22:00.500
It gives you information about all of the output types and everything that you'd want to know about R Markdown.

00:22:00.500 --> 00:22:07.500
I've created a getting started page and a troubleshooting page for PowerPoint output specifically, so I recommend taking a look at those.

00:22:07.500 --> 00:22:14.500
If you have specific questions about your work, then community.rstudio.com is a great place to connect with other people.

00:22:14.500 --> 00:22:22.500
And then if you do find any issues, please let us know by submitting issues to the R Markdown GitHub repo.

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:26.500
I want to address some frequently asked questions.

00:22:26.500 --> 00:22:32.500
There's a question about getting started, about using templates and presentations that we get frequently.

00:22:35.500 --> 00:22:37.500
So this is the getting started page.

00:22:37.500 --> 00:22:41.500
We come down here to templates.

00:22:41.500 --> 00:22:47.500
You can see that the way you set up a template is with this reference doc.

00:22:48.500 --> 00:22:57.500
And the template supports four of the many layouts that are in a PowerPoint template.

00:22:57.500 --> 00:23:05.500
These are the layouts that you want to include in your template for R Markdown documents.

00:23:05.500 --> 00:23:08.500
The first one is the title layout.

00:23:08.500 --> 00:23:12.500
So this will give you the title and the subtitle on this slide.

00:23:12.500 --> 00:23:15.500
The next one is the section header.

00:23:16.500 --> 00:23:23.500
And the section header will only render the header and not the content.

00:23:25.500 --> 00:23:33.500
The title and content slide, which you typically think of as the main slide, and then the two-content layout, which allows you to do columns.

00:23:34.500 --> 00:23:47.500
Now, layouts are important because Markdown doesn't allow you to programmatically change the design or size of your presentation.

00:23:47.500 --> 00:23:59.500
So what it does is Pandoc actually ships with a 4x3 vanilla template that is used to render presentations by default.

00:23:59.500 --> 00:24:10.500
So if you want to use a widescreen format, you're going to have to create a widescreen template and include that as a custom template here in your reference doc.

00:24:10.500 --> 00:24:19.500
If you want to change the background or if you want to change the layout, the placeholders in any way, that's all going to happen with the template.

00:24:23.500 --> 00:24:27.500
The next thing I want to talk about is structuring the presentation.

00:24:27.500 --> 00:24:32.500
This gets a little detailed, but I think it's important to go through.

00:24:32.500 --> 00:24:41.500
PowerPoint presentations have a hierarchy of title, section, and content, whereas Markdown documents have a hierarchy of headers and contents.

00:24:41.500 --> 00:24:50.500
So in order for the PowerPoint presentation to get structured, Pandoc has to determine which Markdown header level should be used for the PowerPoint slide level.

00:24:50.500 --> 00:25:02.500
So for example, in this Markdown document, you have a hierarchy of headers that go from 1 to 5.

00:25:02.500 --> 00:25:10.500
And this header is the one that Pandoc is going to use as the slide level by default.

00:25:10.500 --> 00:25:19.500
And it's going to use it as a slide level because it's the first slide that has content associated with it.

00:25:19.500 --> 00:25:29.500
So everything that gets rendered above this is going to be turned into section slides, and everything below this is going to be turned into subheaders on the content slide.

00:25:29.500 --> 00:25:47.500
Now if you didn't want this to be the content slide and you wanted this to be the slide level, you would change slide level to 2 because 2 would match up to the two hashtags on this R Markdown section header.

00:25:48.500 --> 00:25:55.500
Okay, so you probably don't have to worry too much about this because the defaults should work well for you in most cases.

00:25:55.500 --> 00:26:06.500
If you want to avoid this issue altogether, you can just use the same level header for everything, and then everything will be rendered as content slides.

00:26:07.500 --> 00:26:13.500
The way that the slides get broken up follows these five rules.

00:26:13.500 --> 00:26:23.500
I'm not going to go through all these right now, but just know that there is a way that they get rendered, and there's an easy way to find out what those rules are.

00:26:23.500 --> 00:26:26.500
Just go to the Getting Started page, and it will explain it.

00:26:27.500 --> 00:26:30.500
All right, so troubleshooting.

00:26:30.500 --> 00:26:33.500
What types of issues might you expect to run into?

00:26:33.500 --> 00:26:50.500
Well, some of the common things that we see is that the PowerPoint presentation gets broken, and you get a message that says that it needs to be repaired or removed, or you get this weird one, which doesn't even give you anything at all.

00:26:51.500 --> 00:27:02.500
Typically, the reason for these errors is that the Markdown code that you wrote looks something like this, where everything is condensed together.

00:27:02.500 --> 00:27:11.500
When you write Markdown code, you need to put spaces in between the content, the title, and the speaker notes.

00:27:12.500 --> 00:27:21.500
If you go and put those spaces back in and then restart PowerPoint, PowerPoint is an old program.

00:27:21.500 --> 00:27:25.500
It needs to be restarted every time you get into this weird state.

00:27:25.500 --> 00:27:31.500
If you go back and put the spaces in, restart PowerPoint, this should render more successfully.

00:27:31.500 --> 00:27:33.500
That would be the first thing to try.

00:27:35.500 --> 00:27:38.500
How do I put an image and a text on the same slide?

00:27:38.500 --> 00:27:41.500
There's two ways to put images and text on the same slide.

00:27:41.500 --> 00:27:43.500
One is to use captions.

00:27:43.500 --> 00:27:47.500
If you use a caption in Markdown, it's going to look something like this.

00:27:47.500 --> 00:27:52.500
If you use caption in a code junk, it's going to look something like this.

00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:55.500
You can write very long captions here.

00:27:55.500 --> 00:28:02.500
This is actually a very workable solution, probably the easiest solution to your code.

00:28:03.500 --> 00:28:06.500
Table support captions as well.

00:28:06.500 --> 00:28:08.500
You have to use table caption on those.

00:28:10.500 --> 00:28:13.500
The other way to do it is to use columns.

00:28:13.500 --> 00:28:15.500
This uses the two-content layout.

00:28:15.500 --> 00:28:20.500
You can put your text on one side and your image on the other side.

00:28:20.500 --> 00:28:23.500
You could actually add a caption to this image as well.

00:28:23.500 --> 00:28:28.500
This is a great way to separate text and columns.

00:28:28.500 --> 00:28:32.500
You can put images on both columns or an image on this side and text on the other side.

00:28:35.500 --> 00:28:39.500
The next question, of course, is how do I control the placement of images and text?

00:28:39.500 --> 00:28:43.500
There is no way to do that programmatically.

00:28:43.500 --> 00:28:47.500
You have to do that with the templates, as I mentioned earlier.

00:28:47.500 --> 00:28:54.500
Here what I've done is I've taken the two-content layout in my template,

00:28:54.500 --> 00:28:59.500
and I've stacked one of the content placeholders on top of the other one,

00:28:59.500 --> 00:29:01.500
and it renders quite nicely.

00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:05.500
It allows me to put an image on the bottom and text on the top.

00:29:05.500 --> 00:29:09.500
The only issue here is that you only get one of these,

00:29:09.500 --> 00:29:12.500
so you have to stick with this layout throughout your presentation.

00:29:12.500 --> 00:29:17.500
But this will work really nicely for this layout.

00:29:17.500 --> 00:29:20.500
If you need more programmatic control,

00:29:20.500 --> 00:29:26.500
then you're probably going to be in the situation where you need one of those R packages we talked about earlier.

00:29:26.500 --> 00:29:30.500
How do I control the size of an image?

00:29:30.500 --> 00:29:32.500
Well, you can't.

00:29:32.500 --> 00:29:36.500
Pandoc automatically resizes images to fit a placeholder.

00:29:36.500 --> 00:29:40.500
Currently it's not possible to programmatically change image size.

00:29:40.500 --> 00:29:42.500
How do I create a build slide?

00:29:42.500 --> 00:29:44.500
Build slides are very useful.

00:29:44.500 --> 00:29:48.500
Currently that's not supported, so you can't do a build slide today.

00:29:48.500 --> 00:29:53.500
That's where you click the button and bullet point 1, 2, 3 show up in order.

00:29:53.500 --> 00:29:56.500
How do I render a presentation programmatically?

00:29:56.500 --> 00:29:59.500
We talked about that already through the render command.

00:29:59.500 --> 00:30:01.500
And how do I check my markdown code?

00:30:01.500 --> 00:30:05.500
So sometimes it's useful to check your markdown code if you're trying to debug your rendering process.

00:30:05.500 --> 00:30:10.500
And the way you do that is you use the clean equals false option,

00:30:10.500 --> 00:30:15.500
and that will output the markdown file that gets generated in the rendering process.

00:30:15.500 --> 00:30:25.500
You can open that up and see if it's creating the markdown that you intended to create.

00:30:25.500 --> 00:30:32.500
So all of the things that you saw today were generated in R Markdown with the PowerPoint output,

00:30:32.500 --> 00:30:35.500
including this presentation that you're looking at today.

00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:38.500
This was also generated from an R Markdown document,

00:30:38.500 --> 00:30:47.500
and all of that is stored in a GitHub repo under the Solenge category, and it's called PowerPoint.

00:30:47.500 --> 00:30:51.500
I've included a number of vignettes in here as well that I didn't show today,

00:30:51.500 --> 00:30:55.500
but are very useful in understanding how these features work.

00:30:55.500 --> 00:31:02.500
If you're interested in looking at that, you can download the GitHub repo today and try it out.

00:31:02.500 --> 00:31:07.500
But make sure that you install RStudio version 1.2 preview,

00:31:07.500 --> 00:31:15.500
and you can get there by Googling RStudio preview, downloading the latest copy, and trying this out today.

00:31:15.500 --> 00:31:19.500
So I hope you have a lot of fun making PowerPoint presentations with R Markdown,

00:31:19.500 --> 00:31:22.500
and thank you very much for the time.

